This is a subpage of CategoryModes.  It lists all modes used to edit
markup or to work with markup.  Markup is a bit of text which tells a
processor how to interpret the remaining text.

* RdMode -- simple RD (Ruby Document) syntax highlighting
* CascadingStyleSheetMode -- simple CSS (cascading style sheet) editing mode
* CookingRecipes -- Modes for writing cooking recipes.
* EnrichedMode -- automatic markup added by Emacs to save face information
* GedCom -- genealogy data format
* HtmlMode -- simple HTML editing mode
** ColdFusionDeluxeMode -- HTML and ColdFusion mode with tweaks that may apply to HtmlModeDeluxe variants
** HtmlHelperMode -- HTML editing mode with more features
** HtmlModeDeluxe -- combining psgml-mode, php-mode and css-mode to create a really powerful web development
** NxmlModeForXHTML (part of [NxhtmlMode nXhtml]) -- NxmlMode for XHTML
** QqMode -- a small mode for creating valid XHTML 1.0 Transitional pages
** SpipMode -- a mode for editing http://www.spip.net web page templates
** SmartyMode -- a mode for editing Smarty PHP templates
** YaHTML -- yet another HTML mode
* LaTeX -- simple !LaTeX editing mode
** AUCTeX -- a very powerful !LaTeX environment
* NroffMode -- nroff/troff/groff typesetting and formatting
* PsgmlMode -- for all kinds of SGML markup, if you have a DTD
* RubyTwoMode -- write screenplays (or fiction) and convert to <nowiki>PostScript</nowiki>, HTML, or formatted text.
* XmlMode -- for editing XML (simple sgml-mode, xml-lite, XAE)
* [[Screenplay]] -- for writing movie scripts and screenplays in plain ASCII
* [[reStructuredText]] -- Extended Text Mode, for editing reStructuredText
* TextileMode -- for editing textile markup files
* MarkdownMode -- for editing markdown files
* AsciiDoc -- for editing AsciiDoc files

Modes that take text with peculiar formatting and ''add'' markup:

* BhlMode -- convert brut text into HTML/SGML/LaTeX/Texinfo
* WikiMode and EmacsWikiMode -- convert text into hyperlinked text, and export as HTML (see WikiModes for differences)
* EmacsMuse -- A modular and more generalized derivate of EmacsWikiMode by the same author
* FreexMode -- A personal wiki on steroids - interfaces with a sqlite database to store your metadata, automatically creates hyperlinks to existing pages and provides a sophisticated tagging mechanism
* TableMode -- edit and convert tables to HTML/LaTeX/XML/SGML(TEI)/CALS
* OrgMode -- based on OutlineMode, also exports to HTML

----
